modules.description: Handles conversion of integers to formatted ordinal strings with abbreviations like "1st", "2nd", "3rd", etc. Provides functions to format integers with ordinal suffixes, including options for adding delimiters in larger numbers. Useful for generating human-readable ordinal representations in user interfaces or formatted output.

This module formats 63-bit integers as ordinal numbers with abbreviated suffixes like "st", "nd", "rd", or "th". It provides functions to convert integers to these ordinal strings, optionally with delimiters for readability. Use it when generating human-readable labels such as rankings, positions, or ordered lists with large numbers.

Handles conversion of native integers to ordinal abbreviations and suffixes, including formatted string representations with delimiters. Works directly with `Base.nativeint` values. Useful for generating human-readable ordinal strings in user interfaces or formatted output, such as displaying "1st place" or "1_000_000th visitor".

This module formats 32-bit integers as ordinal strings with suffixes like "st", "nd", "rd", or "th", and supports human-readable formatting with digit delimiters. It provides functions to convert integers to full ordinal strings, to add delimiters for readability, and to extract only the ordinal suffix. Use cases include generating ranked labels (e.g., "1st place") or formatted output for large ordinal values in user interfaces or reports.

This module formats 64-bit integers as ordinal strings with or without digit delimiters and extracts ordinal suffixes. It directly operates on `Base.int64` values, producing string representations like "1st", "2nd", or "1_000_003rd". Use it to generate human-readable ordinal abbreviations for large integers, such as in user interfaces or formatted output.

This module converts integers into their ordinal abbreviation representations, providing functions to generate suffixes and formatted strings. It supports integer types through a provided module and handles large numbers with optional digit delimiters. Use it to produce human-readable ordinals like "1st", "23rd", or "1_000_002nd" for display in user interfaces or reports.

This module converts integers into ordinal abbreviation strings, supporting both basic and formatted output with optional delimiters. It handles all built-in integer types—32, 63, and 64-bit—as well as arbitrary integer types through a functor, producing human-readable suffixes like "1st", "2nd", or "1_000_001st". Functions allow formatting with delimiters, extracting suffixes, and converting native or large integers for use in rankings, UI labels, or reports. Submodules provide type-specific implementations while maintaining a consistent interface for ordinal string generation.
